,"responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced hepatic glucose production","Increased glucose uptake in skeletal muscle","Decreased glucagon secretion from alpha cells","Enhanced glucose excretion by kidneys","Continuous insulin release regardless of blood glucose levels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESulfonylureas cause \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinuous insulin release regardless of blood glucose levels\u003C/strong\u003E by binding to ATP-sensitive potassium channels on pancreatic beta cells. This non-glucose-dependent mechanism means insulin secretion continues even when blood glucose levels fall, leading to hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased glucose uptake in skeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is an effect of insulin, it is not the direct mechanism of sulfonylurea-induced hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased glucagon secretion from alpha cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as sulfonylureas primarily act on beta cells rather than alpha cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced glucose excretion by kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitors, not sulfonylureas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E occurs via insulin\u0027s effects, it is not the primary mechanism of sulfonylurea-induced hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of hypoglycaemia is particularly important in elderly patients and those with irregular eating patterns or renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin release from pancreatic beta cells by binding to ATP-sensitive potassium channels.","The main adverse effect of 